<body lang=EN-GB style='tab-interval:36.0pt'>

<div class=Section1>

<p class=MsoNormal>Your Graces,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>This is a compilation of the report of the travels of
Tagelied HalfElven, loyal servant of the league of Antonican Bards.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I submit it to the High Councils pleasure. </p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Tagelied HalfElven is probably one of the most promising
trainees we have had in living memory.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>He has a fine ear for music, a sense of dedication beyond any of my
experience, and a scholarly, learned attitude.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>He consistently impressed his tutors.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>They mostly seemed to feel that they were training someone for
greatness, an opinion shared by most of his contemporaries, and, it has to be
said, Tagelied himself.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The allocation
of assignments last spring therefore was an even more eagerly awaited event
than usual.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Upon reaching the 6<sup>th</sup>
circle, it is traditional for apprentice bards to be posted to rather more
challenging positions.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>There is a great
deal of speculation upon these assignments by all concerned, and it is widely
believed they are a weathervane for future advancement.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Tagelied had shown great interest in the
work of the historical section of the Guild, and I believe had high hopes of an
assignment to Freeport.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>What he
actually got was Halas.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>The Guild has little involvement
in the city of the Barbarians.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
inhabitants do not produce Bards.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Music, song and even oratory as we know it are unknown to them.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Indeed many in the Guild feel they lack the
cultural advancement necessary for such refined practices.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>However, early in the year, word reached the
Guild of strange and hitherto unknown songs originating from the far
north.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>A Barbarian lady by the name
of<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>“Jallt” was identified as the author
of many of them.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>This was of interest,
partly because of the constant search for new material, but also because it was
such an unlikely source.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Clearly this
new trend of Barbarian music had to be investigated and catalogued.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Accordingly, Tagelied was given
the task of journeying to Halas, finding Jallt and other Barbarian composers,
and recording the material for inclusion in our archives.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>His choice came as a great surprise.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Tagelied is a native of Qeynos and most
proud of his homeland.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Indeed, rarely
has he been known to leave it.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
northlands are bleak, uncivilised and far away.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>The journey is long and dangerous.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>The prospect of travelling to such a place must have been quite
daunting to the urbane and cultured Tagelied.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Certainly at the time he considered it a punishment assignment, and his
earlier reports are filled with bitter railings at the injustice and frantic
enquiries as to the reason for his loss of favor.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>I have taken the liberty of removing most of this material,
partly because it is not relevant and obscures his researches, partly because I
would not want to prejudice his application by presenting words spoken in the
quick temper of youth.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>It is only now that the reasoning
for his choice has become clear.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Tagelied may have been an apprentice of great potential, but he was also
a precocious and proud individual with an inflated sense of his own opinions
and abilities.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>His tutors believed that
exposure to different cultures and ways of thinking would be most beneficial,
teaching tolerance and humility.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Also
they had in mind his determined attitude, a quality that would be needed in
abundance if any sense at all could be made of Barbarian songs.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Their faith has indeed been justified.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Accordingly, I commend the Qeynos
branch of the Guild, and I also heartily recommend Tagelied’s advancement to
the 9<sup>th</sup> circle.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Master Lutestringer, 37<sup>th</sup> Circle, Historical
section.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><u><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>The First Report.<o:p></o:p></span></u></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Your Graces,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>It was early on a typically bright, sunny but cold Qeynos
day, that I took leave of my beloved home city.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>The gates were busy with merchants and guards and the adventurers
of whom it seemed I was now an unwilling member.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>I recall that I appeared detached from the usual hustle and
bustle of the metropolis, as if the city already was foreign to me.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Looking out, the northern reaches beyond
seemed particularly bleak…</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>[Large section cut here – LL]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>I have never been one for travel,
and in fact had only ventured into the hills north of Qeynos on two
occasions.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Accordingly, the Guild had
been good enough to assign two individuals to guide and escort me to
Blackburrow, the only pass through to Halas and home to the Sabretooth tribe of
Gnolls.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'><span style="mso-spacerun:
yes"> </span>I had outfitted myself as well as my purse and expense account
would allow, but my attire still seemed to elicit some amusement from my
companions, who struck me as oafish and uncultured individuals unable to
appreciate beauty or art of any kind.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Their conversation was alternately boorish and non-existent.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Neither seemed to have the slightest
interest in the arts, and I am afraid their motivation in this affair was
confined solely to the receiving of Bardic gold.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>They insisted we started at once,
citing dangers in night travel that I think were grossly exaggerated.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>In spite of their obvious contempt for me, I
had no trouble in keeping up with them, and fair Qeynos rapidly disappeared
from my view, if not from my heart.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
miles passed boringly, an unending tedium of green expanse with a few isolated
and sad-looking trees.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I was so
oppressed that I was moved to take out my drum and play a simple tune I had not
performed in many years.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><u><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>Beat of the Drum.<o:p></o:p></span></u></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Accompaniment – Percussion drum.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Pace: Slow, accelerating.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>From Qeynos town,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a drum, drum, drum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>To faraway lands,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a drum, drum, drum.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Oh, drum, drum, drum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>And we’ll soon come, come,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>We’ll soon go, go,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With the rhythms flow!</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Lets pick up the beat,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a drum, drum, drum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>And we’ll pick up the pace,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a drum, drum, drum.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Oh, drum, drum, drum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Let your fingers strum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>And your heart beats fast,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>While the road goes past.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Lets stretch our legs,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a drum, drum, drum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>And the distance shrinks,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a drum, drum, drum.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Oh, drum, drum, drum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a merry hum,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>And soon we can rest,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>With a glass of the best!</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>This, as your Graces will instantly recognise, is the simple
song Apprentices are taught as a means of learning the first of the challenges
of our craft, namely timing.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I trust
that my simple but elegant variations meet with your approval.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">   </span>It is simple and repetitive – the only
difficulty is the slowly increasing pace.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>I recall many strenuous hours picking through this tune.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Now I laugh inwardly at the thought of
fumbling with such a simple challenge, and yet, strange to relate, I found a
certain comfort in performing it now.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Before I knew it, I was confronted with the threatening open jaw statue
at the entrance to Blackburrow.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>My
escorts gave perfunctory bows, wished me the best of fortune, and disappeared
over the hills back to Qeynos.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>How I
wished at that moment that I could go with them…</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>The Sabretooth Gnolls are a
scourge to the good citizens of Qeynos, and the noble Antonius Bayle has, in
his generosity, offered a great bounty upon their lives.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Consequently many daring individuals come
here to help suppress the foul creatures.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  
</span>As I waited uncertainly by the entrance, all manner of folk came and
went - some with the direst of injuries.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>None paid me more than a cursory glance.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>The entrance seemed dark and forbidding, and I think I may have
been waiting there still, until by the greatest of fortune I saw a fellow bard.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>His name was Berant, and he was
one of five stalwarts about to enter the dim recesses of the Gnollish
stronghold.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>When I explained my
mission, he was pleased to help me, and immediately asked his companions if I
could be allowed to accompany them.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>They were a tough-looking but merry crew, and formed up around me like a
protective shell.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>With so many torches
the interior was far less fearful than I imagined.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>We met only one Gnoll, who went down quickly in a flurry of
sword-strokes.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Soon I was standing by
the exit to Everfrost and the north.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>I wished to learn more of my
companions.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Perhaps they knew of
songs.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It was my mission to gather
them, and we were, technically, now in the northlands.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Sort of.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Besides, the exit was also dark and forbidding, and I deemed it
desirable to obtain a guide.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Perhaps,
in the deeper parts of Blackburrow, I would meet Barbarians about to return to
their homeland, perhaps even one who knew of the mysterious Jallt.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Accordingly, I actually
adventured in Blackburrow.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I am afraid
I was little able to help my companions, but I did see Barbarians, growling in
their bearish tongue.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>In my eagerness I
thought some might be singing, but Berant, who understood a little of the
language, explained that most of what I heard were various imprecations vented
upon hiding or fleeing Gnolls.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I did
not hear a proper song until some hours later, when we stopped by a stone
bridge deep in the mountains for a bite to eat and a short rest.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>As our companions adjusted backpacks and
worked out notches in blades, Berant unhooked his mandolin and played for our
entertainment.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><u><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'>The Lass of Qeynos Hill.<o:p></o:p></span></u></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><b style='mso-bidi-font-weight:normal'><u><span
style='font-size:12.0pt;mso-bidi-font-size:10.0pt'><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></span></u></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Accompaniment – Treble Mandolin.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Pace: Brightly.<br>
<br>
In Qeynos Hills there lives a lass,<br>
More bright than a new day morn,<br>
Whose charms all other maids' surpass,<br>
A rose without a thorn.<br>
This lass so neat,<br>
Who smiles so sweet,<br>
Has won my right good will,<br>
But I'm quite resigned,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>She’ll not be mine,<br>
Sweet lass of Qeynos Hill.<br>
<br>
[Chorus]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Sweet lass of Qeynos Hill<br>
Sweet lass of Qeynos Hill<br>
I'm quite resigned<br>
She’ll not be mine<br>
Sweet lass of Qeynos Hill.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><br>
Ye forest winds that fan the air,<br>
So wanton through the glade,<br>
O whisper to my lover fair,<br>
”I’d die for you my maid”.<br>
This lass so neat,<br>
Who smiles so sweet,<br>
Has won my right good will,<br>
But I'm quite resigned,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>She’ll not be mine,<br>
Sweet lass of Qeynos Hill.<br>
<br>
[Chorus]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><br>
How happy will the suitor be,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Who makes the lass his own.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>If but her choice was fixed on me,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>For mine is on her alone. <br>
This lass so neat,<br>
Who smiles so sweet,<br>
Has won my right good will,<br>
But I'm quite resigned,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal>She’ll not be mine,<br>
Sweet lass of Qeynos Hill.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><br>
[Chorus]</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>There is evidence of future mastery of the songwriting craft
to be had in this ballad.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It is most
exquisitely done, the upbeat melody contrasting with the sad lyrics to produce
a song of great poignancy.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I have seen
such a technique before of course, but never so well executed.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I confess I was puzzled as to how a bard of
but the 11<sup>th</sup> circle could achieve such a masterpiece.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Berant was only too pleased to discuss the
technical aspects of his creation, and I have to say there was nothing very
original in his composition.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I came to
realise that what marked the song out was his performance of it.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Berant was properly modest on this point.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>It was only when I asked him who
the lass in the song was that I came to understanding.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Berant went very still, and answered blandly
that the maid was but a theatrical device, a stylised object for the spurned
lover, and did not exist outside the bounds of his humble ballad.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I could tell however, by the pitying glances
of two of his companions, that this was an untruth.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>I resolved to enquire further of them when he was not present, purely
in the interests of the completeness of this report, you understand.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>My chance came very soon, for within the
space of a few minutes we were assaulted by a pack of Gnolls.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The fight was long and fierce, although
there was never any doubt of the outcome, and I am pleased to report to your
Graces that no damage was done to your humble servant.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Berant received several nasty gashes, and
deemed it prudent to have them bandaged.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>While he was thus preoccupied, I broached the matter of the lass in the
song to his companions.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>They told me
they did not know the name of the lass, but knew that Berant had loved her, and
even that the love was returned.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Unfortunately, her family were not of like mind, and had forbidden the
match.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The lass was loyal and dutiful,
and had put aside her love out of duty to her kin.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>A tale worthy of a ballad indeed.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>I took it upon myself to
investigate the matter further.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>The
cleric of Berant’s party held true to his confessional vows, but from a long
conversation with him that night he did let slip certain facts.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>From this I was able to piece together more
of the story.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I now believe the sweet
lass of Qeynos Hills to be none other than Chanda Miller.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Berant had visited Surefall glade on
numerous occasions, a place the Miller maid frequents, and must have met her
(note the reference to a “glade” in verse two).<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>The lady in question is most fair and skilled, and renowned for
the love and honor in which she holds her brother.<span style="mso-spacerun:
yes">  </span>Baobob is also worthy, but known to be possessive and
overprotective of his sister.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>He would
be unlikely to allow a courtship from an itinerant journeyman bard,
particularly one of mixed parentage.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>Such prejudices I can attest to from personal experience.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>If my supposition is correct, it is a state
of affairs that would be a strain to anyone.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>Your Graces, I am minded once
more of my last lesson from the Guild, on the struggle there is in our
art.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Although I achieved a distinction
in expression (well ahead of the rest of my contemporaries), I must admit that
my knowledge was but culled from a book.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes"> 
</span>A lesson delivered by experience, even second-hand such as in this
affair, dwells in the mind more readily, because it also affects the soul.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>I feel I only understand now the truth that
the greatest ballads are wrung from the heart’s distress.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>If I was to have such an experience
first-hand, I think I might write the greatest love song of all time.<span
style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>It is perhaps well that the ordering of such
things is not at our command, for I am minded that it is a mighty price to pay.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='text-indent:36.0pt'>I would ask your Graces to
consider well the good Berant, and to treat him gently when next he calls at
the Qeynos Guild house.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Treat kindly
also, he who delivers this message, and I pray you reward him appropriately for
his service.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Written this day by my hand,</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>Tagelied HalfElven, of the 6<sup>th</sup> Circle, Antonican
league of Bards.</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

<p class=MsoNormal>(You can find Tagelied, Jallt and Berant on the Tholuxe
Paells server).</p>

<p class=MsoNormal><![if !supportEmptyParas]> <![endif]><o:p></o:p></p>

</div>

